  "stage": {
    "id": "stage_1_inputs",
    "stageNumber": 1,
    "title": "Stage 1: Building the Input Pipeline",
    "roomWidth": 20,
    "roomHeight": 15,
    "concepts": [
      {
        "id": "token_embeddings",
        "title": "From Token IDs to Vectors",
        "content": "Key ideas:\n- shared embedding weights\n- sin/cos PE formula\n\nVaswani et al. (2017) share weights between the embedding tables and the pre-softmax linear layer, scaling them by √d_model. This ties the model's understanding of a token as input and output.",
        "position": {
          "x": 7,
          "y": 6
        },
        "type": "text"
      },
      {
        "id": "attention_head",
        "title": "One Attention Head from Scratch",
        "content": "Key ideas:\n- linear projections\n- scaled softmax\n\nEach head projects inputs to Q, K, V matrices (d_k=64), computes Attention(Q,K,V)=softmax(QKᵀ/√64)V. Without √dₖ scaling, large dot products push softmax into flat regions where gradients vanish.",
        "position": {
          "x": 11,
          "y": 6
        },
        "type": "text"
      }
    ],
    "quiz": {
      "id": "quiz-stage-1",
      "question": "You have dₖ=64. A dot product QKᵀ could reach values around √64=8. Why is dividing by √dₖ important? Answer with a number.",
      "type": "multiple-choice",
      "options": [
        "To normalize outputs to exactly 1.0",
        "To prevent softmax from saturating into near-zero gradients",
        "To reduce the number of parameters"
      ],
      "correctAnswer": "To prevent softmax from saturating into near-zero gradients",
